<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Prep research for the Parcel trait-Enforcer decision
  (<a href="/backlog/756-parcel-trait-enforcer-adapter-resolve-the-plugin-config-deli/">#756</a>) — the
  fifth bundler in the trait-tree-shaking epic
  (<a href="/backlog/715/">#715</a>). The four shipped adapters share <strong>one factory shape</strong>,
  <code>traitEnforcerX(options)</code> taking a JS <code>traitMap</code>, and <strong>one core</strong>,
  <code>buildTraitManifestSource</code> (<code>tools/trait-enforcer/vite-plugin.ts:274-282</code>), wrapped
  per bundler (Vite/Rollup <code>load</code> hook, esbuild <code>contents</code>, webpack
  <code>data:</code> URI). <a href="/backlog/744/">#744</a> <strong>carved Parcel out</strong> because its
  plugin model is <strong>declarative</strong> — a Resolver is referenced <em>by name</em> in
  <code>.parcelrc</code> and instantiated by Parcel, so (the reasoning went) the Map can't be a JS factory
  argument. #756 is the fork over <em>how the Map reaches the resolver</em>.
</p>

<h2>What the survey found</h2>

<h3>1 · The virtual-module mechanism is sound</h3>
<p>
  A Parcel <code>Resolver</code>'s <code>resolve()</code> returns a <code>ResolveResult</code> whose
  <strong><code>code</code></strong> field is exactly a virtual module —
  <em>"the code of the resolved asset; if provided, this is used rather than reading the file from
  disk."</em> So the Parcel adapter is a Resolver that, for the virtual id, returns
  <code>{ filePath: virtualId, code: buildTraitManifestSource(options) }</code>, reusing the shared core
  unchanged (the <code>() =&gt; import(spec)</code> thunks then code-split like every other bundler).
  Resolvers run as a <strong>pipeline</strong> — return <code>null</code> to pass to the next — so the
  adapter only handles its own id. This is a forced invariant, not a fork.
</p>

<h3>2 · A named <code>.parcelrc</code> plugin gets config via <code>loadConfig</code>, not JS args</h3>
<p>
  <code>.parcelrc</code> registers plugins <strong>by name</strong> in arrays and carries
  <strong>no inline plugin options</strong>. The idiomatic way a named plugin reads project config is the
  <code>loadConfig</code> hook calling <code>config.getConfig([files], { packageKey })</code> — it searches
  <em>up the directory tree</em> for the named files (JSON5 default, also JS/TOML) and a
  <code>package.json</code> key, exactly as the Sass transformer does:
  <code>getConfig(['.sassrc', '.sassrc.js'], { packageKey: 'sass' })</code>. Docs stress using Parcel's
  loader so the cache invalidates correctly; avoid reading files directly. Plugin naming convention is
  <code>parcel-resolver-&lt;tool&gt;</code> (or scoped).
</p>

<h3>3 · The load-bearing finding — v2.9.0 relative-path plugins let the factory survive</h3>
<p>
  Since <strong>Parcel v2.9.0</strong>, a plugin can be referenced in <code>.parcelrc</code> as a
  <strong>relative path</strong> to a local JS file — <em>"they don't need their own
  <code>package.json</code>; you can reference a JavaScript file directly."</em> This <strong>overturns
  #744's premise.</strong> A project can author a tiny local resolver that imports a WE factory and passes
  the Map as a JS argument captured in a closure:
</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code>// parcel-resolver-trait-enforcer.js  (project-local, relative-path in .parcelrc)
import { traitEnforcerParcel } from '@frontierui/trait-enforcer/parcel';
export default traitEnforcerParcel({ traitMap: { sortable: '…', 'export-csv': '…' } });</code></pre></we-code-view>
<p>
  where <code>traitEnforcerParcel(options)</code> returns a <code>Resolver</code> that returns
  <code>{ filePath: virtualId, code: buildTraitManifestSource(options) }</code> for the virtual id. This
  <strong>preserves the cross-bundler <code>traitEnforcerX(options)</code> symmetry</strong> — all five
  adapters take <code>options.traitMap</code> as a JS arg — with no new config format and no published
  package. So the genuine fork is <em>not</em> "the Map can't be a JS arg" but
  <strong>declarative-config vs local-wrapper</strong>.
</p>

<h2>The reshaped decision shape</h2>
<p>
  The single muddled "factory options vs <code>.parcelrc</code> + config file" question becomes
  <strong>one real call</strong> plus invariants that aren't decisions:
</p>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Element</th><th>Recommended</th><th>Main alternative</th><th>Confidence</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Virtual module mechanism</td>
      <td><code>resolve()</code> returns <code>{ filePath, code }</code> from the shared core</td>
      <td>— (forced invariant)</td>
      <td>High</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>.parcelrc</code> registration</td>
      <td>Hand-authored + documented (like all four adapters)</td>
      <td>— (forced invariant)</td>
      <td>High</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>How the trait Map reaches the resolver</strong></td>
      <td><strong>B — local wrapper preserving the factory</strong> (v2.9.0 relative-path)</td>
      <td>A — idiomatic <code>.trait-enforcerrc</code> / packageKey via <code>loadConfig</code></td>
      <td>Med-high</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>
<p>
  <strong>B</strong> keeps the epic's "one Map, every bundler" symmetry, introduces no new project-facing
  config format (in line with <em>minimize-lock-in / refuse project-facing formats</em>), and matches how
  every other adapter is consumed (the project wires it into build-config JS). Its one caveat — the Map
  isn't loaded through Parcel's cache-aware <code>loadConfig</code> — is covered by an
  <code>invalidateOnStartup</code> declaration, since the Map is build-time static.
  <strong>A</strong> is the principled main alternative (most native-Parcel, cache-correct) but mints a new
  config-file schema and breaks the JS-factory symmetry. <strong>C — WE-generated config</strong> is
  rejected (WE writing project-owned files violates minimize-lock-in).
</p>

<h3>Dep scope correction</h3>
<p>
  A real Parcel build (for the #722 conformance rows) needs the full
  <code>@parcel/config-default</code> stack plus <code>@parcel/plugin</code> — <strong>not</strong> just
  <code>@parcel/core</code> as #744 assumed. The conformance test references the resolver by
  <strong>relative path</strong> (v2.9.0), so no published package is needed to verify.
</p>

<h2>Web-standards alignment</h2>
<p>
  The adapter borrows Parcel's own plugin vocabulary (Resolver, <code>resolve()</code> /
  <code>loadConfig</code>, <code>ResolveResult.code</code>, <code>invalidateOnStartup</code>) rather than
  coining a bespoke wiring, in keeping with WE's native-first / minimize-lock-in principles. WE owns the
  neutral trait-manifest contract and the shared core; the bundler integration stays Parcel-native.
</p>

